/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25798177/yukai_robot_2.jpg\" data-old-src=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\"/\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ccite\u003eImage: Yukai Engineering\u003c/cite\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cp\u003eMirumi is a robot that you might actually want to own. It’s a furry, bashful companion bot that clings to a bag and looks adorable. It doesn’t have AI tricks and doesn’t even make noise. Like my colleague Owen Grove said \u003ca href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@verge/video/7456601160565263658?embed_source=121374463%2C121468991%2C121439635%2C121433650%2C121404359%2C121477481%2C121351166%2C121487028%2C73226838%2C121331973%2C120811592%2C120810756%2C121494655%3Bnull%3Bembed_blank\u0026amp;refer=embed\u0026amp;referer_url=www.theverge.com%2F2025%2F1%2F5%2F24325152%2Fyukai-engineering-mirumi-robot-ces\u0026amp;referer_video_id=7456601160565263658\"\u003ein a video\u003c/a\u003e: “It’s just a cute fuzzy thing. What more do you want?” It will be available through a crowdfunding campaign that’s set to launch in mid-2025.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ch3\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2025/1/6/24335423/acer-handheld-gaming-pc-nitro-blaze-8-11-specs-price\"\u003eAcer Nitro Blaze 11\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cdiv role=\"button\" aria-label=\"Zoom\" tabindex=\"0\"\u003e\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"A person holding an Acer Nitro Blaze 11.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-nimg=\"fill\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1023px) 100vw, 744px\" srcset=\"https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:3840x2160/376x212/filters:focal(1920x1080:1921x1081):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25815999/Nitro_Blaze_11_GN7112U_lifestyle_2.jpg 376w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:3840x2160/384x216/filters:focal(1920x1080:1921x1081)